ğŸ™ What is GitHub?

**GitHub** is a cloud-based platform used to **store, manage, and collaborate on code**.
It works on top of **Git**, which tracks changes in your project.

ğŸ“Œ GitHub = online platform
ğŸ“Œ Git = version control tool

---

ğŸ†š Git vs GitHub

| Git                 | GitHub             |
| ------------------- | ------------------ |
| Tool                | Platform           |
| Works locally       | Works online       |
| Tracks code changes | Hosts repositories |
| CLI-based           | Web + Git          |

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ“¦ What is a GitHub Repository?

A **GitHub Repository (Repo)** is an **online project folder** that contains:

* Source code
* Commit history
* Branches
* Documentation (`README.md`)
* Issues & Pull Requests

ğŸ“Œ Think of it as your **projectâ€™s online home**

---

ğŸ—‚ï¸ Contents of a GitHub Repository

* Code files
* `README.md`
* `.gitignore`
* Commits
* Branches
* Issues
* Pull Requests (PRs)

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸŒ Public vs Private Repositories

| Public Repo         | Private Repo     |
| ------------------- | ---------------- |
| Visible to everyone | Limited access   |
| Good for portfolio  | Company projects |
| Free hosting        | Secure           |

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”„ Basic GitHub Workflow

1. Create repository on GitHub
2. Clone repo to local system
3. Create a branch
4. Make changes
5. Commit changes
6. Push changes
7. Create Pull Request
8. Merge into main

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§ª Important GitHub Commands

Clone Repository

```bash
git clone <repo-url>
```

Check Branches

```bash
git branch
```

Push Code

```bash
git push origin main
```

Pull Latest Changes

```bash
git pull origin main
```

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸŒ¿ Git Branching

What is a Branch?

A **branch** is a **separate version of your code** that allows you to work independently without affecting the main code.

ğŸ“Œ Default branch â†’ `main`

---

Why Branching is Important

* Work on new features safely
* Fix bugs without breaking main code
* Multiple developers can work together
* Cleaner and safer development


Creating & Switching Branches

Create a New Branch

```bash
git branch feature-login
```

Switch to Branch

```bash
git checkout feature-login
```

Create & Switch (Shortcut)

```bash
git checkout -b feature-login
```

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸŒ¿ Types of Branches

* `main` â†’ production-ready code
* `feature` â†’ new features
* `bugfix` â†’ fixing bugs
* `hotfix` â†’ urgent fixes


ğŸ”€ Git Merging

What is Merging?

**Merging** means combining changes from one branch into another (usually into `main`).

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Merge Workflow

1. Switch to main branch

```bash
git checkout main
```

2. Merge feature branch

```bash
git merge feature-login
```

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”€ Pull Requests (PR)

A **Pull Request** is a request to **merge one branch into another** using GitHub.

Why PRs are Important

* Code review
* Team discussion
* Quality control
* Safe merging

ğŸ“Œ Used in **all companies**

